enable the creation of more realistic and expressive avatars for applications in virtual reality (VR), augmented reality (AR), and human-computer interaction (HCI). It will advance the field of 3D human modeling and animation by providing a method to generate avatars from casual, everyday videos, which are more accessible than specialized 3D scans or RGBD images. This research could lead to practical applications in entertainment, education, and telecommunication, enhancing user experience and interaction capabilities.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "The problem is challenging due to the limited diversity of facial expressions and poses in short monocular videos, which makes it difficult to create a fully expressive avatar. Additionally, the absence of 3D observations leads to ambiguity in occluded parts, causing artifacts in animations. Naive approaches may fail because they do not adequately address these issues, often resulting in inaccurate or unrealistic avatars. Technical challenges include handling occlusions, ensuring photorealism, and maintaining the drivability of the avatar with novel expressions and poses.",\n\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has focused on either body motions without facial expressions and hand motions or required specialized 3D observations, which are not available in most casual videos. Existing volumetric avatars lack connectivity, and previous 3D Gaussian Splatting-based works do not consider the connectivity between 3D Gaussian points. The proposed hybrid representation addresses these gaps by combining the drivability of SMPL-X with the photorealistic rendering of 3D Gaussian Splatting, while also introducing connectivity between 3D Gaussians.",\n\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "The proposed methodology involves creating a hybrid representation of the surface mesh and 3D Gaussians in ExAvatar, where each 3D Gaussian is treated as a ve